1
00:00:47,380 --> 00:00:49,769
Okay, all right, hold up.

2
00:00:49,965 --> 00:00:53,404
Someone has to say something
nice about my friend Herb tonight,

3
00:00:53,635 --> 00:00:56,024
so I'm gonna give it a shot.

4
00:00:56,220 --> 00:00:59,576
I have followed Herb Lee
my whole writing career.

5
00:00:59,807 --> 00:01:04,164
I followed him through three publishing
houses, and when he started his own.

6
00:01:04,435 --> 00:01:09,350
It's embarrassing to need your editor
so badly, so I'm gratified to announce

7
00:01:09,648 --> 00:01:13,402
that he has now followed me
to Central Connecticut. Thank you.

8
00:01:13,651 --> 00:01:16,006
I didn't follow you,
I had three heart attacks.

9
00:01:16,195 --> 00:01:18,834
This was a pre-emptive strike
against decrepitude.

10
00:01:19,030 --> 00:01:21,590
Well, whatever brought you here

11
00:01:21,782 --> 00:01:24,421
to the beautiful
Marigold Retirement Community,

12
00:01:24,618 --> 00:01:28,247
I just want to say I'm glad you're here,
right down the road from my place,

13
00:01:28,496 --> 00:01:31,727
and as long as Pippa
keeps making that butterflied lamb,

14
00:01:31,957 --> 00:01:34,266
I'll do anything.
I'll even caddy for you.

15
00:01:34,459 --> 00:01:37,019
That's fine,
as long as I don't have to play golf.

16
00:01:37,211 --> 00:01:40,169
Wait, one more thing.
I just want to say something else.

17
00:01:40,381 --> 00:01:43,214
I have known Pippa Lee for 25 years...

18
00:01:44,467 --> 00:01:47,459
<i>...and I think
that I will never really know her.</i>

19
00:01:47,678 --> 00:01:50,954
She is a mystery. An enigma.

20
00:01:51,181 --> 00:01:56,539
Giving, caring, beautiful, intelligent,

21
00:01:56,852 --> 00:01:59,286
the very icon of an artist's wife.

22
00:01:59,479 --> 00:02:02,357
- What are you talking about?
- No, you are.

23
00:02:02,565 --> 00:02:05,637
And who precisely is this artist
that Pippa is married to?

24
00:02:05,859 --> 00:02:07,850
Exactly!

25
00:02:08,028 --> 00:02:10,667
Yes, that's my point!
That's what it's come down to.

26
00:02:10,863 --> 00:02:13,855
The one true artist's wife
left in the modern world,

27
00:02:14,074 --> 00:02:16,065
and she ended up with a publisher.

28
00:02:16,242 --> 00:02:19,552
To Herb and Pippa
and their weird new condo.

29
00:02:19,787 --> 00:02:23,143
Yeah, I just, er, got three new poems.

30
00:02:23,373 --> 00:02:27,571
Wonderful. If you'd ever like to show
them to somebody who's non-judgemental,

31
00:02:27,835 --> 00:02:30,144
- I'd be happy to take a look at them.
- Really?

32
00:02:30,337 --> 00:02:33,329
I would like that.
That would mean so much to me.

33
00:02:33,548 --> 00:02:36,540
I wish Sam wouldn't keep saying
Daddy moved to be near him.

34
00:02:36,759 --> 00:02:40,547
He's a satirist. Anyway, nothing's
going to put a dent in Herb's ego.

35
00:02:40,804 --> 00:02:42,795
It's you I'm worried about.

36
00:02:44,598 --> 00:02:46,236
It's time for dessert.

37
00:02:46,391 --> 00:02:49,986
But, Herb, what is the real reason
you moved here?

38
00:02:50,228 --> 00:02:52,537
Scaling down, making life more simple.

39
00:02:52,730 --> 00:02:55,722
I've liquidated everything
so that when I go,

40
00:02:55,941 --> 00:02:59,411
Pippa and the kids can get everything
and not give it to the government.

41
00:02:59,652 --> 00:03:01,961
I thought you loved paying taxes.

42
00:03:02,154 --> 00:03:05,305
I have to admit, I actually like
this house. It's so easy.

43
00:03:05,532 --> 00:03:07,807
I'm glad you feel that way, sweetie.

44
00:03:08,784 --> 00:03:11,981
Though I can't help wondering
how many people have died here.

45
00:03:12,204 --> 00:03:16,482
Your problem is you're too adaptable.
You're the adaptable enigma.

46
00:03:21,169 --> 00:03:25,321
<i>To be perfectly honest,
I've had enough of being an enigma.</i>

47
00:03:29,884 --> 00:03:31,875
<i>I wanna be known.</i>

48
00:03:38,057 --> 00:03:41,333
<i>Like many people,
I have lived more than one life,</i>

49
00:03:41,560 --> 00:03:44,120
<i>so we're going to have to start
at the beginning.</i>

50
00:03:44,312 --> 00:03:46,985
Breathe. Breathe.
- Shut up!

51
00:03:48,357 --> 00:03:50,871
I see the head. Come on, one good push!

52
00:03:51,068 --> 00:03:53,423
Oh, fuck you!

53
00:03:53,612 --> 00:03:55,762
Good girl.

54
00:03:55,947 --> 00:03:59,178
<i>My birth was marked
by several unusual occurrences.</i>

55
00:03:59,408 --> 00:04:02,798
<i>First of all,
I was covered in fine blonde fur.</i>

56
00:04:05,204 --> 00:04:07,957
- Why is she furry?
- That's nothing to worry about.

57
00:04:08,165 --> 00:04:11,237
When a baby's this late,
it has time to grow vestigial hair,

58
00:04:11,459 --> 00:04:13,290
from the time that we were monkeys.

59
00:04:14,211 --> 00:04:18,443
I had a monkey! I had a monkey!

60
00:04:18,715 --> 00:04:21,434
You can expect to have
a beautiful baby girl.

61
00:04:21,634 --> 00:04:24,592
The hair is just vestigial,
as I tried to tell your wife.

62
00:04:24,803 --> 00:04:28,955
I'm sorry if it offends you, Father, but
we believe that millions of years ago,

63
00:04:29,223 --> 00:04:31,691
- humans were covered with fur.
- I know that.

64
00:04:31,892 --> 00:04:34,122
So, is it a baby or a pet?

65
00:04:34,311 --> 00:04:38,020
<i>Suky knew my condition
had nothing to do with evolution.</i>

66
00:04:38,272 --> 00:04:42,424
<i>It was all her fault,
because my mother had a secret,</i>

67
00:04:42,692 --> 00:04:45,570
<i>her own little stash of sin.</i>

68
00:04:51,741 --> 00:04:54,699
- How's my pal?
- I'm OK.

69
00:04:56,662 --> 00:04:59,699
Are you having a hard time
living here in Wrinkleberry?

70
00:04:59,914 --> 00:05:04,704
It's strange having so much time on my
hands. This place is easy to maintain,

71
00:05:05,002 --> 00:05:07,641
but there's gonna be charity work
I can find.

72
00:05:07,837 --> 00:05:11,068
- You wanna move back to the city?
- We just sold our apartment.

73
00:05:11,298 --> 00:05:14,574
- Well, we can get another one.
- Are you serious?

74
00:05:14,801 --> 00:05:16,439
No.

75
00:05:17,637 --> 00:05:22,028
I'm just having a hard time
thinking of this as the end of the line.

76
00:05:25,351 --> 00:05:30,709
I think it's sort of romantic...
starting all over, just the two of us.

77
00:05:31,022 --> 00:05:32,614
So little stuff.

78
00:05:32,774 --> 00:05:35,766
Must you always look at the bright side?

79
00:05:39,154 --> 00:05:41,270
Can I get you anything?

80
00:05:41,447 --> 00:05:44,644
- Some carrot juice?
- No, I'm fine.

81
00:05:50,079 --> 00:05:52,752
What was that cheese
we had for lunch yesterday?

82
00:05:52,956 --> 00:05:57,154
It was vacherin. I was so excited
to find that at the market.

83
00:05:57,418 --> 00:05:59,409
I love that cheese.

84
00:06:11,596 --> 00:06:14,429
<i>Once I lost my furry coat,
my mother was so relieved</i>

85
00:06:14,640 --> 00:06:17,837
<i>that she became sort of obsessed
with my appearance.</i>

86
00:06:18,060 --> 00:06:20,574
<i>She even took a drawing course
at the town hall,</i>

87
00:06:20,770 --> 00:06:23,603
<i>the sole purpose of which
was making pictures of me.</i>

88
00:06:23,814 --> 00:06:27,204
Sweetheart,
you have the most beautiful eyes.

89
00:06:27,442 --> 00:06:31,196
I think God took all of our best
features and put them on your face.

90
00:06:31,445 --> 00:06:34,198
Don't you move. Almost done.

91
00:06:40,077 --> 00:06:44,036
Why, you little...
Turkey, turkey, turkey, turkey.

92
00:06:44,289 --> 00:06:45,802
Ouch!

93
00:06:48,501 --> 00:06:52,255
<i>She dressed me up as angels,
cowgirls, movie stars.</i>

94
00:06:53,963 --> 00:06:56,033
<i>I was her prize possession.</i>

95
00:06:56,215 --> 00:06:58,683
<i># You're real, real cool</i>

96
00:06:58,884 --> 00:07:00,442
<i># For you I'm a fool</i>

97
00:07:01,511 --> 00:07:03,979
<i>- # Teen baby, be mine
- # Honey, I will</i>

98
00:07:04,180 --> 00:07:07,809
<i>- # Teen baby, be mine
- # Honey, you know I will</i>

99
00:07:08,058 --> 00:07:09,889
<i># Baby, be mine</i>

100
00:07:10,685 --> 00:07:12,596
<i># All of the time</i>

101
00:07:13,354 --> 00:07:15,072
<i># Oh, don't you know</i>

102
00:07:16,023 --> 00:07:17,615
<i># I love you so</i>

103
00:07:18,608 --> 00:07:20,997
<i>- # Glad you're my date
- # Do-do, do-do-do</i>

104
00:07:21,193 --> 00:07:23,661
<i># With me, you're great
Teen baby, be mine</i>

105
00:07:50,216 --> 00:07:54,368
Who else has a key?
- The cleaning lady.

106
00:07:57,389 --> 00:08:00,665
But I can't see Miss Fanning
breaking in with a few friends

107
00:08:00,892 --> 00:08:03,725
to have chocolate cake
in the middle of the night.

108
00:08:03,936 --> 00:08:06,734
- And the maintenance people?
- You think it was me?

109
00:08:06,938 --> 00:08:11,409
- You think I'm losing my marbles?
- I wasn't saying that. I wasn't...

110
00:08:11,692 --> 00:08:13,683
- Hey.
- There she is.

111
00:08:13,860 --> 00:08:15,930
Hi, Daddy.

112
00:08:16,112 --> 00:08:18,307
- You look great.
- Oh, thanks.

113
00:08:18,489 --> 00:08:20,798
- Hey, Mom.
- Hi.

114
00:08:20,991 --> 00:08:24,142
- I'm starving. Can I get lamb chops?
- Anything you want.

115
00:08:24,369 --> 00:08:27,247
- Do you want a drink first?
- Yeah.

116
00:08:27,454 --> 00:08:30,605
Oh, Ben says, er,
he can't make it until later,

117
00:08:30,832 --> 00:08:33,221
- so we should just order without him.
- OK.

118
00:08:33,417 --> 00:08:36,807
OK, these are just work prints, but...

119
00:08:37,045 --> 00:08:39,434
- Oh, my God.
- You get the idea.

120
00:08:41,132 --> 00:08:44,886
That's incredible. It's amazing, even.

121
00:08:45,135 --> 00:08:47,968
Were you in a doorway? Where were you
when you took this?

122
00:08:48,179 --> 00:08:51,330
Yeah, I just waited there.
I knew they were coming back.

123
00:08:51,557 --> 00:08:54,754
That's incredibly powerful.
Look at this.

124
00:08:56,811 --> 00:08:59,245
Oh!

125
00:08:59,438 --> 00:09:02,828
- These are so... powerful.
- These are wonderful.

126
00:09:03,066 --> 00:09:07,139
Grace, this... Hmm.

127
00:09:07,403 --> 00:09:11,112
- Were you alone when you took these?
- No, we had a guide.

128
00:09:11,364 --> 00:09:12,399
You had a guide?

129
00:09:12,532 --> 00:09:15,569
And I hitched a ride with,
erm, Giles Oppenheim.

130
00:09:15,785 --> 00:09:17,457
- With Giles Oppenheim?
- Hm-hmm.

131
00:09:17,619 --> 00:09:20,770
- How did you manage that?
- He kind of adopted me.

132
00:09:20,997 --> 00:09:24,467
Did you hear about that photographer
that got shot in Baghdad last week?

133
00:09:24,708 --> 00:09:26,141
Uh-huh.

134
00:09:26,293 --> 00:09:30,764
You heard about the bomb?

135
00:09:31,047 --> 00:09:33,322
- Ben, shut up.
- What bomb?

136
00:09:33,507 --> 00:09:35,498
- She was with Oppenheim.
- Ben!

137
00:09:35,675 --> 00:09:38,951
<i>And they heard the whistle.</i>

138
00:09:39,178 --> 00:09:42,568
And he wanted to go left,
but she saw an alley towards the right,

139
00:09:42,806 --> 00:09:46,116
and she pulled him towards it,
and that's when the bomb hit.

140
00:09:46,351 --> 00:09:48,501
They turn around,
and if they'd gone left,

141
00:09:48,686 --> 00:09:51,075
they would have been
smashed to smithereens.

142
00:09:51,271 --> 00:09:54,581
- She thinks she's immortal now.
- That's a complete distortion.

143
00:09:54,816 --> 00:09:57,967
- Why can't you ever not say something?
- I do not know.

144
00:09:58,193 --> 00:10:01,868
Sweetheart, everybody knows you're
a killer but you gotta be careful.

145
00:10:02,113 --> 00:10:05,389
- You have to use your common sense.
- I do. Dad, look...

146
00:10:05,616 --> 00:10:07,846
There's no way
that I'm not gonna go back.

147
00:10:08,034 --> 00:10:10,867
If you had seen what I saw,
you would feel the same.

148
00:10:11,079 --> 00:10:13,991
You would want to give these people
some dignity.

149
00:10:14,206 --> 00:10:17,596
- Just be careful.
- Anyway, I'm going to Baghdad Saturday.

150
00:10:17,834 --> 00:10:23,670
- What's new with you?
- Oh, I found a book. A real cash cow.

151
00:10:24,005 --> 00:10:27,918
Since when do you say "cash cow"?

152
00:10:28,175 --> 00:10:30,928
I never said it
because I never found one before.

153
00:10:31,136 --> 00:10:36,005
- What's it about?
- Oh, it's about war and romance,

154
00:10:36,307 --> 00:10:38,867
- and, er, bad weather.
- Is it good?

155
00:10:39,059 --> 00:10:44,133
A certain kind of good. Highbrow
for lowbrows or lowbrow for highbrows.

156
00:10:44,438 --> 00:10:47,828
Summer reading for people
with multimillion-dollar beach homes.

157
00:10:48,066 --> 00:10:51,376
- Used to be us.
- We still wouldn't have read this book.

158
00:10:51,611 --> 00:10:54,887
So, how are you, Ben?
How is your paper coming?

159
00:10:55,114 --> 00:10:57,184
- Fine.
- What's it about?

160
00:10:57,365 --> 00:10:59,959
- The right to die.
- The right to die?

161
00:11:00,159 --> 00:11:04,311
Or the right to kill.

162
00:11:13,920 --> 00:11:17,913
<i># A sweet little kiss with a wee embrace
A pretty little smile</i>

163
00:11:18,174 --> 00:11:22,452
<i> Suky's energy was unflagging,
day and night.</i>

164
00:11:25,763 --> 00:11:29,039
<i>In spite of
an apparently weak thyroid,</i>

165
00:11:29,266 --> 00:11:32,258
<i>for which she took pills
at seven each morning,</i>

166
00:11:32,477 --> 00:11:37,835
<i>12 noon, and four each afternoon,
I was the only one who knew</i>

167
00:11:38,148 --> 00:11:42,107
<i>that she was secretly pretending
to be in a commercial half the time,</i>

168
00:11:42,359 --> 00:11:44,748
<i>or a movie, and she was the star.</i>

169
00:11:46,071 --> 00:11:52,146
<i>- I thought she was absolutely perfect.
- Mom, can I have some more milk? Mom?</i>

170
00:11:52,493 --> 00:11:56,452
<i>Then there were days when Suky
shorted out,</i>

171
00:11:56,704 --> 00:11:59,776
<i>- like a run-down robot.
- Eat up, kids.</i>

172
00:11:59,999 --> 00:12:03,548
<i>I always felt my real mother
had disappeared in those moments.</i>

173
00:12:03,793 --> 00:12:07,149
<i>It scared me and made me angry.</i>

174
00:12:11,424 --> 00:12:13,892
<i>I thought it must be my fault
that she was sad,</i>

175
00:12:14,093 --> 00:12:16,653
<i>and it was up to me
to make her happy again.</i>

176
00:12:26,686 --> 00:12:30,395
<i>I thought maybe
you forgot to say goodnight. </i>

177
00:12:37,278 --> 00:12:39,394
<i>Her moods ruled my life.</i>

178
00:12:46,119 --> 00:12:48,952
<i>My baby.</i>

179
00:12:54,083 --> 00:12:56,472
Oh, hello, Dot.

180
00:12:56,669 --> 00:13:00,662
- Would you like some coffee?
- Oh, no, I-I've already had some.

181
00:13:00,922 --> 00:13:03,994
- This is my son, Ben.
- Oh, the lawyer?

182
00:13:04,216 --> 00:13:06,935
Not yet. Nice to meet you.

183
00:13:07,135 --> 00:13:10,127
- And Herb. You met Herb.
- Oh, hi, Herb.

184
00:13:10,346 --> 00:13:12,655
Oh, my Lord.

185
00:13:12,848 --> 00:13:18,081
That's Mr Swaggart.
He needed to go.

186
00:13:18,394 --> 00:13:20,544
Erm, h-have a seat.

187
00:13:20,729 --> 00:13:23,687
You know, there are
other young wives here.

188
00:13:23,899 --> 00:13:27,130
You see them jogging around.

189
00:13:27,360 --> 00:13:31,751
- Is everything OK?
- Well, yes, we're... We're fine.

190
00:13:33,073 --> 00:13:36,349
But my son, erm, Chris...

191
00:13:37,868 --> 00:13:40,302
- In Utah?
- Yes.

192
00:13:40,495 --> 00:13:43,328
He might be coming... east.

193
00:13:43,539 --> 00:13:46,451
Oh, that should be nice,
if they would move near you.

194
00:13:46,667 --> 00:13:51,661
The thing is, he's had some kind
of crisis with his wife, and...

195
00:13:51,963 --> 00:13:54,761
He's left her, and he's...

196
00:13:54,965 --> 00:13:59,880
He's living in his car.
I just don't know what to do.

197
00:14:00,177 --> 00:14:06,650
He was always sort of half baked.
You know what I mean?

198
00:14:10,686 --> 00:14:13,678
You know, it's painful, I know...

199
00:14:15,648 --> 00:14:20,164
<i>...but sometimes you just have to maybe
accept they are who they are.</i>

200
00:14:21,611 --> 00:14:24,762
I mean, I-I feel that with my daughter.

201
00:14:24,989 --> 00:14:26,980
You're right.

202
00:14:27,157 --> 00:14:32,595
I knew that I should come to you.
You... I just had a feeling.

203
00:14:34,288 --> 00:14:37,837
-  He's living in his car?
- Yes, she said he was half baked.

204
00:14:39,042 --> 00:14:42,114
- I wonder what that means.
- It's code. It means halfwit.

205
00:14:42,336 --> 00:14:44,770
Hello?

206
00:14:46,131 --> 00:14:48,361
Hello, Marianne.

207
00:14:48,549 --> 00:14:52,337
What? What?

208
00:14:52,594 --> 00:14:56,109
No, tell him 45
is the absolute top offer.

209
00:14:57,556 --> 00:15:00,070
If he goes somewhere else,
he goes somewhere else.

210
00:15:00,267 --> 00:15:03,816
Stop worrying. Everything's fine.
You're doing a fantastic job.

211
00:15:04,062 --> 00:15:08,260
Have a nice morning, Marianne.
God, that woman's gonna drive me crazy.

212
00:15:08,524 --> 00:15:12,073
Your blood pressure went
from 120 over 90 to 148 over 100.

213
00:15:12,318 --> 00:15:14,752
Since when did you become a nurse?

214
00:15:14,945 --> 00:15:16,378
A little appreciation...

215
00:15:16,530 --> 00:15:19,488
Would you like to go to the doctor's
every 15 minutes?

216
00:15:19,699 --> 00:15:21,212
We gotta change our number.

217
00:15:21,367 --> 00:15:24,439
- I need an office.
- What is the point of having an office?

218
00:15:24,661 --> 00:15:27,459
The point is I spent 40 years
building up this company

219
00:15:27,664 --> 00:15:30,940
and they're crapping it up.
They're children there. Babies.

220
00:15:31,167 --> 00:15:33,761
If I had an office,
I can be there from ten to one,

221
00:15:33,960 --> 00:15:38,636
talk to Marianne, read my manuscripts,
and when I come home, boom, I'm retired.

222
00:15:38,923 --> 00:15:41,118
Then we can be really together.

223
00:15:41,300 --> 00:15:44,690
You had three heart attacks.
Is that not enough for you?

224
00:15:44,927 --> 00:15:47,600
Yeah.

225
00:15:47,805 --> 00:15:50,035
- I gotta go.
- Bye, sweetheart.

