After you get your fish.

691
00:56:55,143 --> 00:56:57,418
I'll make pasta.

692
00:56:58,562 --> 00:57:00,757
Where do you want to go?

693
00:57:03,233 --> 00:57:06,305
<i>I don't know.  Erm...</i>

694
00:57:06,527 --> 00:57:10,361
- I could show you where I grew up.
- OK.

695
00:57:13,408 --> 00:57:15,205
How do I get there?

696
00:57:15,367 --> 00:57:20,441
It's straight for a couple of miles.
Then we'll make a turn. I'll tell you.

697
00:57:20,747 --> 00:57:23,056
It's close.

698
00:57:23,749 --> 00:57:25,421
There it is.

699
00:57:33,924 --> 00:57:37,473
- Seems so small.
- Is your family still here?

700
00:57:39,136 --> 00:57:41,127
No.

701
00:57:46,517 --> 00:57:49,748
That's my daughter, Grace. She hates me.

702
00:57:52,355 --> 00:57:54,152
I wonder...

703
00:57:55,566 --> 00:57:58,717
- What?
- If I got it all wrong with her.

704
00:58:00,278 --> 00:58:03,350
I just didn't want to suffocate her
the way my...

705
00:58:05,866 --> 00:58:10,303
I think it happens like that in families
sometimes, though.

706
00:58:10,578 --> 00:58:14,366
You just keep swinging back and forth
from generation to generation,

707
00:58:14,623 --> 00:58:18,013
getting it wrong, the opposite way.

708
00:58:21,670 --> 00:58:23,979
It was so simple with Ben.

709
00:58:27,133 --> 00:58:31,649
But you know, she, erm,
is a photographic journalist.

710
00:58:31,928 --> 00:58:35,967
Travels all over the world, wherever
it's exploding, takes photographs.

711
00:58:36,223 --> 00:58:37,895
- Wow.
- Yeah, I know.

712
00:58:38,058 --> 00:58:40,208
We must have done something right.

713
00:58:43,021 --> 00:58:45,171
Sounds like your daughter's like you.

714
00:58:47,357 --> 00:58:51,066
- Why?
- You said you were always in a drama.

715
00:58:54,029 --> 00:58:56,782
Well, I was reckless with my life,
that's true.

716
00:59:07,165 --> 00:59:09,281
I never saw her again.

717
00:59:12,044 --> 00:59:14,399
- Who?
- My mother.

718
00:59:14,587 --> 00:59:17,977
After I ran away, she died.
She had a heart attack.

719
00:59:20,801 --> 00:59:22,996
Oh, I can't wait to see.

720
00:59:25,388 --> 00:59:27,379
<i> If I could have anything,</i>

721
00:59:27,556 --> 00:59:30,468
<i>I would ask for one more afternoon
with my mother.</i>

722
00:59:30,683 --> 00:59:32,958
Look at her eyes.

723
00:59:33,144 --> 00:59:35,294
<i> I would be kind.</i>

724
00:59:35,479 --> 00:59:37,470
Beautiful.

725
00:59:45,112 --> 00:59:47,387
I've been going to Dot's pottery class.

726
00:59:47,572 --> 00:59:51,611
- Oh, good.
- Why do you think it's good?

727
00:59:51,867 --> 00:59:54,586
The doctor said
he thought you could use a hobby.

728
01:00:01,875 --> 01:00:04,992
- Tell me what you like about me.
- Right now?

729
01:00:05,211 --> 01:00:07,202
Yeah.

730
01:00:08,589 --> 01:00:11,581
- You put up with me, for one thing.
- That's it?

731
01:00:11,799 --> 01:00:13,994
Of course not.

732
01:00:16,595 --> 01:00:21,988
Herb, what happened to us? We used to
laugh so much. What happened?

733
01:00:22,308 --> 01:00:25,618
- Can't laugh all the time.
- Well, we have to laugh.

734
01:00:25,852 --> 01:00:27,968
- Or what?
- Or she died for nothing.

735
01:00:28,146 --> 01:00:31,104
- Not that again, OK?
- Why am I not allowed to mention her?

736
01:00:31,315 --> 01:00:35,228
I will not let this marriage turn into
a guilt fest. We have been through this.

737
01:00:35,485 --> 01:00:38,522
She was crazy. You get involved
with somebody like that,

738
01:00:38,738 --> 01:00:42,253
it's like putting your hand
in a blender. Your fingers get bloody.

739
01:00:42,491 --> 01:00:45,244
I just can't take it, I can't take it.
I keep seeing her.

740
01:00:45,451 --> 01:00:47,840
I keep seeing her. I keep...

741
01:00:49,371 --> 01:00:53,159
I keep seeing the past.
The past just keeps caving in.

742
01:00:54,542 --> 01:00:58,501
<i>I can't take it any more.
I can't take it.  I'm sorry.</i>

743
01:01:03,966 --> 01:01:06,639
Maybe you should be taking
antidepressants.

744
01:01:11,597 --> 01:01:13,110
What?

745
01:01:20,771 --> 01:01:23,569
You alright? You want to talk?

746
01:01:23,773 --> 01:01:26,651
My mother used to do this.
She'd suddenly disappear,

747
01:01:26,859 --> 01:01:30,374
and I'd find her on the bed in front of
the TV with toast on her belly.

748
01:01:30,612 --> 01:01:33,251
- That's how she died.
- Yes, I know.

749
01:01:34,824 --> 01:01:37,702
- I have to take your blood pressure.
- No, you don't.

750
01:01:53,756 --> 01:01:57,431
<i> I slept for a week
after the party at Herb's beach house.</i>

751
01:02:00,803 --> 01:02:03,556
<i>Maybe I was trying to avoid
my next boyfriend.</i>

752
01:02:06,099 --> 01:02:09,694
<i>When I woke up, I felt an overwhelming
need to hear Herb's voice.</i>

753
01:02:11,228 --> 01:02:14,186
<i>I missed him so much. It was strange.</i>

754
01:02:53,511 --> 01:02:55,900
<i> Hello?</i>

755
01:02:56,097 --> 01:03:01,490
<i>- Er, Mr Lee? Hi, it's Pippa Sarkissian.
- Pippa!</i>

756
01:03:01,810 --> 01:03:06,326
Hey. I-I was wondering,
do you want to go out to breakfast?

757
01:03:06,605 --> 01:03:12,202
<i>- It's three o'clock in the afternoon.
- I meant tomorrow.</i>

758
01:03:14,778 --> 01:03:18,691
<i> He treated me like a pal
at first. He was avuncular.</i>

759
01:03:18,948 --> 01:03:22,907
<i>He teased me about being a waster.
I called him an old fart.</i>

760
01:03:23,160 --> 01:03:27,312
<i>We would get together every couple of
days and take a walk or eat something.</i>

761
01:03:27,580 --> 01:03:31,493
<i>He gave me reading lists.
He wanted to educate me.</i>

762
01:03:33,210 --> 01:03:36,247
- Hey. Sorry I'm late.
- You're always late.

763
01:03:36,462 --> 01:03:39,022
Well, maybe you're always early.

764
01:03:40,299 --> 01:03:44,690
I bought something for you.
Now, you only have to wear this once.

765
01:03:44,969 --> 01:03:47,324
I'll be alone at the beach house
this weekend,

766
01:03:47,513 --> 01:03:50,710
and I want you to come for lunch.

767
01:03:50,932 --> 01:03:53,844
- You weren't supposed to buy this.
- I needed to.

768
01:03:54,060 --> 01:03:58,815
<i> I loved being with Herb.
He made me feel protected.</i>

769
01:03:59,105 --> 01:04:00,936
<i> I thought I was a writer.</i>

770
01:04:01,107 --> 01:04:05,146
I thought it was my calling,
but it just wasn't. I, er...

771
01:04:06,695 --> 01:04:08,287
I-I couldn't flow.

772
01:04:08,446 --> 01:04:12,917
I have a very critical nature,
and it kept me from being able to flow.

773
01:04:13,200 --> 01:04:18,433
Then I... was slightly lost for a while.
I had no idea what I was gonna do,

774
01:04:18,746 --> 01:04:22,864
and I had a friend in the publishing
business, and he offered me a job.

775
01:04:23,124 --> 01:04:25,354
- And here I am.
- Hmm.

776
01:04:30,797 --> 01:04:32,947
Tell me what you like about me.

777
01:04:35,301 --> 01:04:39,533
Well, you're not a show-off about it,
but I think you're very intelligent,

778
01:04:39,804 --> 01:04:44,002
and... you're beautiful,
but you're cool about it,

779
01:04:44,266 --> 01:04:47,224
and there's a sadness about you,

780
01:04:47,435 --> 01:04:51,826
and I like that, in moderation.

781
01:04:53,399 --> 01:04:57,915
- I like your jacket.
- And that's it?

782
01:04:59,111 --> 01:05:01,386
No.

783
01:05:01,572 --> 01:05:04,484
No, I...

784
01:05:06,701 --> 01:05:09,420
I like your face and your voice...

785
01:05:10,621 --> 01:05:13,931
<i>...and, erm...</i>

786
01:05:14,165 --> 01:05:17,157
- This is gonna sound strange.
- Say it.

787
01:05:19,086 --> 01:05:21,077
It's like, erm...

788
01:05:22,672 --> 01:05:25,584
Like I can feel what you're feeling.

789
01:05:25,799 --> 01:05:30,395
You know, if you feel nervous
or happy or sad, I can feel it.

790
01:05:31,929 --> 01:05:34,648
I-In my body, in my fingers.

791
01:05:36,099 --> 01:05:39,853
- What a remarkable thing.
- Oh.

792
01:05:40,102 --> 01:05:43,458
I'd like you not to feel as if you have
to censor yourself around me.

793
01:05:43,689 --> 01:05:47,887
Tell me something about yourself. Tell
me the most important thing about you.

794
01:05:51,528 --> 01:05:53,678
I'm a fuck-up.

795
01:06:01,661 --> 01:06:05,017
<i> I felt like I was being
rescued from a burning wreck.</i>

796
01:06:05,247 --> 01:06:07,602
If I'm good for anything in the world,

797
01:06:07,791 --> 01:06:10,669
it's for letting you know
how wonderful you are.

798
01:06:14,088 --> 01:06:16,443
You're my true wife, you know?

799
01:06:17,799 --> 01:06:21,917
No, you don't want me.
I only make people sad.

800
01:06:22,178 --> 01:06:24,248
I don't believe that.

801
01:06:27,557 --> 01:06:30,788
Anyway, you have a wife.

802
01:06:32,394 --> 01:06:37,104
If I have to live with that lunatic
for another week, I'll hang myself.

803
01:06:37,398 --> 01:06:40,674
For years, I've hoped she'd have
an affair so I can walk out on her,

804
01:06:40,901 --> 01:06:44,450
but she won't do it, the bitch.

805
01:06:56,246 --> 01:07:02,162
Mrs Lee still seems unwilling to work
her way up like the rest of us.

806
01:07:04,378 --> 01:07:09,088
- Oh, go stick it up your ass.
- What did you say to me?

807
01:07:16,763 --> 01:07:18,640
I don't understand.

808
01:07:18,806 --> 01:07:21,195
She agrees to divorce
if we have lunch with her?

809
01:07:21,391 --> 01:07:24,064
She wants to make the switch
in an elegant way.

810
01:07:24,269 --> 01:07:26,544
I can't believe you agreed to this!

811
01:07:26,729 --> 01:07:29,402
I owe her this much. Come on, let's go.

812
01:07:29,606 --> 01:07:31,995
Hello, Mr Lee. Nice to see you.
Hello, miss.

813
01:07:32,192 --> 01:07:34,660
- Hello, Alphonsa.
- Welcome.

814
01:07:34,860 --> 01:07:37,738
Hi, hi. Hello, hello, hello.

815
01:07:42,867 --> 01:07:45,222
- Hi.
- Sam! What a pleasant surprise.

816
01:07:45,410 --> 01:07:47,640
I told Ursa to bring in the champagne.

817
01:07:47,829 --> 01:07:50,423
- Perfect symmetry.
- What?

818
01:07:50,623 --> 01:07:55,413
- Come on.
- She invited me for lunch.

819
01:07:57,628 --> 01:08:00,188
Stop! Cheers.

820
01:08:05,009 --> 01:08:10,527
- Oh. You're such a baby.
- Thanks.

821
01:08:10,847 --> 01:08:14,396
<i> Let's face it,
I wanted Gigi's life at that moment.</i>

822
01:08:14,642 --> 01:08:16,633
<i>It wasn't the money, exactly.</i>

823
01:08:16,810 --> 01:08:19,722
<i>It was just that the money
made everything seem alright.</i>

824
01:08:19,938 --> 01:08:24,170
<i>It was the opposite of chaos,
of everything I had known up until then.</i>

825
01:08:24,441 --> 01:08:26,432
<i>I wanted to be sheltered at last.</i>

826
01:08:29,737 --> 01:08:33,047
- Madam.
- Lunch is served.

827
01:08:33,282 --> 01:08:34,351
Oh, my.

828
01:08:36,785 --> 01:08:38,218
Pippa?

829
01:08:39,328 --> 01:08:40,807
Herb.

830
01:08:43,874 --> 01:08:46,627
This lunch is in honour
of telling it like it is.

831
01:08:47,752 --> 01:08:50,107
You know how we all eat chops
and hamburgers,

832
01:08:50,295 --> 01:08:53,412
and we don't think of the faces
of who gets killed?

833
01:08:55,091 --> 01:08:58,401
- Anybody here a vegetarian?
- Here's the truth as I see it.

834
01:08:58,635 --> 01:09:03,789
- A pig for a cow. A fair exchange.
- And who's who?

835
01:09:04,890 --> 01:09:07,643
- Sorry.
- OK, let's have lunch. Who wants pig?

836
01:09:07,851 --> 01:09:10,285
- First, a toast.
- Aw, jeez!

837
01:09:11,396 --> 01:09:13,387
To transformation.

838
01:09:27,575 --> 01:09:28,974
Put the gun down.

839
01:09:30,828 --> 01:09:32,819
Put it down.

840
01:09:34,664 --> 01:09:36,700
Put it down, Gigi.

841
01:09:37,958 --> 01:09:40,677
Isn't it funny how men
always marry women

842
01:09:40,877 --> 01:09:45,155
who are easier and easier to dominate,
until they end up with an imbecile?

843
01:09:45,423 --> 01:09:48,017
Put the gun down.

844
01:09:50,593 --> 01:09:52,584
Put it down.

845
01:10:00,143 --> 01:10:02,577
Give me the... No!

846
01:10:21,743 --> 01:10:24,541
<i> Her image would haunt me
for the rest of my life.</i>

847
01:10:28,290 --> 01:10:31,600
<i>I knew without thinking
that not only would I marry Herb,</i>

848
01:10:31,835 --> 01:10:34,747
<i>I would give myself to him,
like a penitent.</i>

849
01:10:36,171 --> 01:10:39,004
<i>This was my last chance at goodness.</i>

850
01:10:39,215 --> 01:10:42,571
<i>If I fucked this up,
I would be fallen forever.</i>

851
01:10:42,802 --> 01:10:47,592
<i>Every day I tried to be good,
to erase the past.</i>

852
01:10:47,889 --> 01:10:50,323
<i>I stopped getting high.</i>

853
01:10:50,516 --> 01:10:53,314
<i>But I didn't know
how to be this new person.</i>

854
01:10:53,518 --> 01:10:57,830
<i>Like a dancer learning a new routine, I
relied on repetition to teach my brain.</i>

855
01:10:58,105 --> 01:11:00,255
Hello? Hello?

856
01:11:00,441 --> 01:11:02,511
Hello?

857
01:11:02,692 --> 01:11:07,527
<i>It wasn't till I had the babies though
that I really believed my own act.</i>

858
01:11:07,821 --> 01:11:11,257
<i>That was when Pippa Sarkissian
disappeared forever.</i>

859
01:11:12,867 --> 01:11:15,381
<i>That was how I became Pippa Lee.</i>

860
01:11:16,829 --> 01:11:22,506
I got thrown out of pottery class.
I got thrown out of pottery class!

861
01:11:28,797 --> 01:11:31,709
- Who is it?
- It's me.

862
01:11:31,924 --> 01:11:33,915
I'll be right there.

863
01:11:36,678 --> 01:11:40,034
- Everything OK?
- I got thrown out of pottery class.

864
01:11:40,264 --> 01:11:44,303
- Why?
- I told the teacher to screw off.

865
01:11:44,559 --> 01:11:46,868
Let me get my keys.
We'll get some coffee.

866
01:11:47,061 --> 01:11:50,053
She's a witch. She's...

867
01:11:51,106 --> 01:11:53,859
Why is this towel here, sweetheart?

868
01:11:54,067 --> 01:11:57,377
Were you eating, and you didn't
want to mess up the couch?

869
01:11:58,070 --> 01:11:59,423
No.

870
01:12:02,448 --> 01:12:03,722
What?

871
01:12:32,305 --> 01:12:36,981
- When did this start?
- Sometime after we moved here.

872
01:12:40,187 --> 01:12:46,023
I was hoping it was an affair,
but... it just isn't.

873
01:12:46,358 --> 01:12:50,909
I-I know this has got to be...
dreadful for you.

874
01:12:51,195 --> 01:12:55,871
I... I want you to have all the money.
You deserve everything.

875
01:12:56,158 --> 01:12:59,867
Thanks. Erm, well,
are you going to marry her?

876
01:13:00,119 --> 01:13:04,795
Well, at my age, it would be
pretty ridiculous, wouldn't it?

877
01:13:05,081 --> 01:13:08,869
And... I just wanna live.

878
01:13:09,126 --> 01:13:13,005
The past few years, I can feel you
starting to bury me, Pippa.

879
01:13:13,255 --> 01:13:17,726
I can feel the earth in my mouth, almost
as if you're looking forward to it.

880
01:13:18,008 --> 01:13:21,080
- How can you say that?
- I can feel you starting to pity me,

881
01:13:21,303 --> 01:13:25,740
being afraid of me.
You're already mourning. Don't deny it.

882
01:13:26,932 --> 01:13:30,083
I mean, of course, I-I am afraid
of you getting old and dying.

883
01:13:30,310 --> 01:13:32,380
It's normal to be afraid.

884
01:13:32,562 --> 01:13:35,872
Well, I don't want to be normal
or mourned. I am not a ghost!

885
01:13:36,106 --> 01:13:38,939
I wanna live!
Nobody knows when they're gonna die.

886
01:13:39,150 --> 01:13:43,382
You could die tomorrow, and fuck you
for making me feel like an old man!

887
01:13:43,654 --> 01:13:47,329
<i>But, Herb, you are an old man.</i>

888
01:13:51,952 --> 01:13:55,991
Oh, my... Oh, Sandra!

889
01:13:57,081 --> 01:13:59,231
Killing yourself
with a disposable razor.

890
01:13:59,416 --> 01:14:01,930
<i>I don't think
anyone's ever done that before.</i>

891
01:14:03,128 --> 01:14:06,040
She was in despair, you know.
She loves you.

892
01:14:06,255 --> 01:14:09,372
This first-aid kit came in handy,
didn't it?

893
01:14:14,512 --> 01:14:18,027
<i> I had the strangest feeling
walking down those stairs.</i>

894
01:14:18,265 --> 01:14:20,779
<i>I suddenly felt so light,</i>

895
01:14:20,975 --> 01:14:23,887
<i>as if a great weight
had been lifted off of me.</i>

896
01:14:36,112 --> 01:14:39,627
<i> Remember this moment,
sports fans. Remember where you were.</i>

897
01:14:39,865 --> 01:14:42,504
<i>Pippa Lee rounding the bend,
guilt baton in hand,</i>

898
01:14:42,701 --> 01:14:45,773
<i>coming up on Sandra Dulles,
and the pass is complete!</i>

899
01:14:45,995 --> 01:14:48,748
<i>Pippa Lee has passed
the guilt baton to Sandra Dulles!</i>

900
01:14:48,956 --> 01:14:51,231
<i>I never thought
I'd live to see this moment!</i>

901
01:15:25,193 --> 01:15:27,184
- Hi, there.
- Hi.

902
01:15:37,661 --> 01:15:39,652
What's going on?

903
01:15:41,748 --> 01:15:45,184
My husband has been having an affair
with a good friend of mine.

904
01:15:46,502 --> 01:15:48,493
So...

905
01:15:51,047 --> 01:15:53,720
<i>...it's official.
Nobody needs me any more.</i>

906
01:16:21,154 --> 01:16:25,067
- Hi, Ma.
- Dot!

907
01:16:26,158 --> 01:16:28,626
- Wait.
- Dot! No, no, no.

908
01:16:28,827 --> 01:16:31,819
Please, I didn't mean to upset you.
I really didn't.

909
01:16:32,038 --> 01:16:35,030
- That man is 35 years old.
- But we haven't done...

910
01:16:35,249 --> 01:16:40,926
And you are whatever you are.
It's none... It's none of my beeswax.

911
01:16:41,253 --> 01:16:44,563
It is just disappointing

912
01:16:44,798 --> 01:16:48,950
when someone turns out not to be
the person you thought they were.

913
01:16:56,057 --> 01:16:57,934
I lost control.

914
01:17:02,062 --> 01:17:05,896
I... I care about you tremendously.

915
01:17:07,274 --> 01:17:12,712
Why don't I feel anything? I mean, it
can't be that I don't love you any more.

916
01:17:13,029 --> 01:17:17,181
- I-I adored you only this morning.
- Maybe you're in shock.

917
01:17:17,449 --> 01:17:21,601
- It's all so tired.
- What is?

918
01:17:21,869 --> 01:17:25,578
This whole situation.
Let's just fast-forward to the divorce.

919
01:17:48,515 --> 01:17:50,506
